A.  OVERVIEW

The myriad changes in Russia following the dissolution of the former Soviet
Union in 1991 have initiated a major transformation in Russia's health care
services and industry.  For many decades, medical care in Russia and the
former Soviet Union was primarily a state-run business, with very few
exceptions.  Now some former state-run facilities have been privatized, and
specialized medical clinics are being created with western equipment and
techniques.  As a result, rising medical costs and new medical services have
become a reality for the average Russian citizen.  This transformation
process has created a new market for western products, techniques and
equipment in Russia.

The focus of this industry sector analysis is on the market for Home Health
Care Equipment in Russia.  Specifically, it is directed towards equipment
utilized in the home health care industry as the term is understood in the
West and in Russia, which includes:

1.  Devices, instruments, supplies and simple diagnostic equipment, such as
inhalers, liquid thermometers, water filters, tonometers, and massage
equipment that can be self-administered by a patient in his own home for
illness prevention and for self-treatment of non-serious medical ailments.

2. Equipment which is provided by clinics or hospitals for a patient's
rehabilitation after a curable disease has been diagnosed, including massage
and exercise equipment.  Under these circumstances, this equipment would be
used under hospital/clinic supervision.

3.  Equipment used by ambulance or emergency medical services or portable
equipment that can be transported by physicians on home visits with their
patients.  Electrocardiographs, portable ultrasound, and fast blood
diagnostic equipment fall under this category.

The major changes in Russian health care are stimulating a totally new demand
for home health care products.  Since this is a new industry subsector for
Russia, it is not possible to provide detailed statistics.  However, domestic
demand for these products is expected to grow substantially over the next
several years.

The major end-users of home health care equipment are: state-run
organizations, pharmacies, private distribution companies, non-state clinics
and hospitals, medical insurance companies and existing manufacturing
enterprises.

Best prospects for U.S. exporters are indicated as follows: inhalers
(including oxygen and ultrasound), tonometers, stetofonendoscopes,
sphignomonometers, massage equipment, ozonizers, portable medical equipment,
ultraviolet equipment, first aid kits, digital display thermometers and
disposable therapeutic and surgical supplies as well as simple diagnostic
equipment/kits.

With the increasing number of foreign companies entering the local market,
Russian importers are paying close attention to the international reputation
of the manufacturer, the price-quality relationship of the products and the
advertising support provided by the exporter.

Background of the Russian Health Care System

As health care in Russia is changing, so is the "doctor-patient"
relationship, creating a new market for home health care equipment, as
follows:

1.  Russians now have to pay more to receive higher quality medical services
and better hospital conditions, as well as for certain specialized medical
procedures and pharmaceuticals.  As a result, patients are becoming more
cost-conscious and are calculating their financial resources.  This is
forcing patients to cut short their hospital stays and to have less frequent
visits to their doctors.  Patients are gaining interest in having more
procedures available in their homes, resulting in a growing interest in home
health care equipment.

2.  In some regions of Russia, especially in the North-West, various official
(state) medical care facilities are starting programs based on the concept of
the "family doctor".  For this reason, there is a definite need for home
health care equipment, especially portable diagnostic equipment.  Under the
same program and in line with the new developments in private and state
health care programs, an increased demand for ambulance equipment has been
created as well.

3.  As pharmaceuticals and health care costs are becoming an expensive
endeavor, Russians are becoming more health conscious and are considering
alternative medicine.  Some medical enterprises are now moving quickly in an
effort to develop preventive medicine techniques and procedures and the means
for self-treatment.  This includes home health care equipment.

In order to understand this new demand for home health care, it is important
to have an appreciation of the Russian health care system.  In general,
former Soviet and Russian citizens have received routine medical treatment
free of charge.  This included treatment at the wide range of local district
clinics throughout Russia with different medical specialists, including
physiotherapy and non-complicated surgery.  These district clinics have a
number of general practitioners on staff who see patients in a clinic and in
patients' homes.  For example, in St. Petersburg there are 98 district
clinics for the city's inhabitants.  For serious diseases or complicated
illnesses, general practitioners often sent their patients to a specialist
working in the same clinic, who together with a general practitioner, would
make a decision regarding further treatment.

Some enterprises and professional unions (such as for actors, communication
workers, or army officers) maintain their own clinics as well as hospitals
and sanatoriums.  These "professional" clinics are better equipped and have
better services than the district clinics and have more qualified personnel
on staff attracted by their higher salaries.  There are 37 "professional"
clinics in St. Petersburg, including the former communist party hospitals and
clinics that still possess the most privileged facilities in terms of
the quality of equipment and services.  After the Perestroika period in
Russia (1985-1991), these facilities declared themselves "independent" from
the state and became limited companies.

Another category of medical enterprises is medical institutes which focus
primarily on specialized medical problems, such as cardiology, pediatrics,
etc.  They also have their respective clinics and hospitals for these
specialized treatments.

In general, when a Russian citizen is ill he goes through the same steps in
health care service as in Europe or in the United States.  But there are at
least two important points of difference:

1.  The quality of the equipment in Russia is generally much poorer than
European or American medical equipment.  This fact, together with the lower
professional level of medical personnel in most of the clinics and
ambulances, makes medical care in Russia less effective.

2.  Home health care equipment is not used for treatment or rehabilitation as
a part of regular medical service.  In the above-mentioned facilities, home
health care equipment was neither available nor utilized; all treatment took
place in the facilities themselves.

As the above description of the Russian health care system indicates, home
health care in Russia currently is in a very primitive stage.


