C.  MARKET ASSESSMENT

It was only two years ago that home health care equipment started to appear
at Russian Trade Shows.  Originally, this equipment was oriented towards use
in sports medicine, such as massage equipment and different types of exercise
equipment.  However, it was soon discovered that this equipment could have
different applications, such as for rehabilitation following illness or
surgery.  Ironically, the patients themselves made this discovery in
1991-1992.

Today, the domestic market for home health care equipment is in its earliest
stage of development but is showing signs of rapid growth.  For example, it
was only in 1992 that public solariums started to appear in St. Petersburg.
By the end of 1993, close to 300 were in the city.

There are new tendencies in the Russian health care industry including the
concept of home health care.  As a result, average Russian citizens are now
procuring first aid kits for their homes with basic essentials for both
sickness prevention and treatment.  Citizens suffering from chronic illnesses
such as asthma are also taking steps to acquire medicines and equipment for
home use.

In the larger cities, such as Moscow, St. Petersburg and Vladivostok, special
"family doctor" programs are being created.  The main premise of the programs
is similar to the family practitioner concept used in the United States.
Some medical insurance companies are also organizing similar programs, and
medical insurance programs in general are being revamped.

Pursuant to a Central Russian Government Decree, effective January 1, 1993,
all enterprises in Russia are required to pay a percentage of their profit
(3.4%) to the local government's insurance fund.  A portion of this money
goes to the Federal Government budget for the Russian Ministry of Health to
support state medical programs.  The rest is divided by the local
administration among certain medical insurance companies which also receive
money from the federal budget.  Therefore, local insurance funds have two
sources of financing: from local and federal budgets.  In 1993 the share
provided by the local government to the St. Petersburg local insurance fund
was 6.0 billion Rbl. (5.2 million USD).  The federal share totalled 9.0
billion Rbl. (7.8 million USD).

The local government insurance fund, as well as the designated medical
insurance companies, retain 5% of the proceeds for their purposes.  Medical
insurance companies divide the rest of the funds among state-run clinics and
hospitals as directed by the local administration.  The share of each clinic
and hospital is determined according to the number of their potential
patients, which is calculated from the number of inhabitants (for district
offices) or workers (for "professional" enterprises).

In addition, medical insurance companies are lobbying for increased funding
from the federal government's insurance budget to offer new forms of health
care for the population.  One of the ideas which the insurance companies are
trying to launch is a "family doctor" program.  Their idea differs from the
state medical care point of view because they believe that the "family
doctor" should be a private enterprise under the control of and sponsored by
a medical insurance company.  They are proposing a system whereby a patient
seeking medical care from his doctor is only required to sign a voucher and
all or a portion of the payment is provided by the medical insurance company.

Under their system, insurance companies believe that the "family doctor"
would be more interested in lending certain equipment to the patient for
necessary self-administered medical care and relying less on time spent on
doctors' visits and hospital stays.  The changes in the Russian insurance
industry and the new directions in medical care in general are expected to
stimulate demand for more expensive and more complicated home health care
equipment in the market over the next 2-3 years.

As state medical care changes and affects medical insurance policy, former
district clinics are also converting to "family doctor" clinics, with funding
from the central insurance budget.  The same process is occurring with state
hospitals.  Consequently, a real market is opening for more expensive and
more efficient medical equipment for the patient's home use under hospital
supervision.  This transformation of medical institutions also is creating an
immediate demand in the market for low cost home health care equipment which
can be provided to the patients.

Customer Profile

There are currently five primary categories of customers in the Russian
health care market:

1. State-run organizations: institutions including Health Committees and
medical enterprises, such as sanitary committees and state-run clinics and
hospitals.  Health Committees are a part of each local administration.  For
example, St. Petersburg has one City Health Committee and 21 District Health
Committees.  Health Committees direct the local development of the state
medical programs and the operations of state clinics and hospitals.  They
also supervise the distribution of insurance funds and federal funds for
medical development.  Most of the above-mentioned institutions are financed
from the government budget.  They are currently one of the most important
buyers of home health care equipment.  Purchasing decisions are made on a
case-by-case basis, with the Chairman or Director as the final
decision-maker.

2. Pharmacies: local groups of retail outlets and wholesalers that operate as
company chains and mostly sell supplies and equipment.  For example, St.
Petersburg has 250 pharmacies grouped in approximately 25-30 chains.  Each
chain consists of 7-12 pharmacies which include both state-run and private
entities.

3. Private distribution companies: distributors which are seeking new market
opportunities and have prior experience working as wholesalers for such
consumer goods as cosmetics, toiletries and  household supplies.  Many view
the emerging home health care industry as an underdeveloped and very
promising sector.

4. Non-state (private) clinics and hospitals: also potential end-users for
home health care equipment and, in particular, of portable diagnostic and
treatment equipment.  The heads of these institutions make their own
decisions on certain purchases.  Their purchasing power depends on their
financial status and management orientation which may be geared towards
simple and inexpensive equipment, or expensive and complicated medical
equipment and services.

5. Medical insurance companies: new potential players in this market.
However, it is too early to provide a concrete analysis of their potential
demand.  Their role is a function of the development of the health insurance
industry and the amount of government subsidies which they receive.

6. Existing manufacturing enterprises: the most "eager-to-cooperate"
potential partners at the moment since they are seeking alternatives for the
survival of their companies in the face of decreasing federal subsidies.  At
the same time, they have experienced human resources and operate with
relatively modern equipment.  They are included in the list of end-users as
the best potential partners for manufacturing of home health care equipment,
which may include some conversion of their production base, and/or
modernization and expansion of their existing facilities.

The end-user shares of market demand are estimated as follows:

State organizations               - 40%
Pharmacies-wholesalers            - 37%
Private companies                 - 10%
Non-state clinics and hospitals   - 10%
Insurance companies               -  3%
Manufacturing enterprises         - undetermined


D.  BEST PROSPECTS

Currently, Russians do not completely understand home health care equipment.
Nevertheless, local experts expect a rapid increase in interest in this
equipment, with high market demand  by 1995-1996.  The best prospects for
U.S. exporters vary according to the targeted end-user.  Overall, it is
expected that local market tendencies will lean heavily toward home health
care equipment for private use, such as ozonizers, water and air filters.
However, there are good prospects for certain equipment directed at
professional end-users.

The market for home health care is generally divided into professional
end-users and those who use equipment for private use.

Professional-use equipment primarily covers the needs of ambulances and
emergency medical services.  The best prospects for this group are first aid
kits and portable diagnostic equipment.  There also is a market in the
clinics, hospitals and newly emerging "family doctor" enterprises for
portable equipment, such as sphignomonometers, negatoscopes, portable
electrocardiographs, and ophthalmoscopes.

Private-use equipment includes less-sophisticated equipment available over
the counter that can be used by individuals without professional medical
supervision.  This equipment should be easy and convenient to use.

One factor to consider is the income level of Russian consumers as well as
the purchasing power of the professional end-users.  The income level of
about 90% of the population is strikingly low compared to western salaries,
with an average salary below $100 per month.  This large group of potential
endusers is interested in purchasing low-end, inexpensive products such as
hot-water bottles and inhalers.  Pricing plays a key role for this segment.
However, there is also a small but growing sector of "new rich" Russians (up
to 10% of the population in major Russian cities) who can afford more
expensive and sophisticated products such as solariums at $4000 each.

