E.  COMPETITIVE SITUATION

Domestic Production

There are at least 4 types of local producers of home health care equipment
in Russia today:

1.  State and former state enterprises and factories that historically have
produced medical equipment, including equipment for private use.  For
example, the "Krasnogvardeyets" Factory located in St. Petersburg produces
tonometers that are sold for 30,000-40,000 Rubles ($25-30) in retail stores.
It produces  approximately 300,000 pieces per year throughout Russia.  These
institutions still receive some state support.

2.  Private enterprises that are generally small and were formed to meet the
market demand in the medical field, especially in non-complicated equipment.
Their average turnover generally does not exceed $5000 per month.  These
enterprises receive no state support and are striving to develop the
necessary management and organizational skills to enable them to survive in a
competitive market.  This category includes private enterprises founded by
combining several scientific research institutes with similar interests.  Due
to the higher quality of their products, these new enterprises have a strong
position on the local market.

The St. Petersburg Institute of Preventive Medicine is an example.  The
Institute is a conglomerate consisting of several research institutes and
small manufacturing firms involved in production of simple equipment such as
inhalers - 500,000 pieces/year with a retail price of 300-800 Rubles
($.30-.60), respiratory exercise equipment - 600,000 pieces/year for 150-250
Rubles ($.10-$.20) a piece, and air-ozonizers - 1,200,000 pieces/year with a
retail price of 1100-2500 Rubles ($.90-2.80).

3. Defense Conversion enterprises, which are just entering the market.  Until
recently these enterprises were involved in manufacturing for the defense
sector and had significant state investments.  They still possess modern
equipment and therefore have good potential to become some of the most active
and important competitors on the local market.  For example, in St.
Petersburg, such enterprises include the "Bolshevik" factory that is now
producing wheelchairs at their facilities, and the LOMO association which is
planning to start a production of simple pediatric diagnostic kits.

As statistics indicate, the local production of medical equipment has
declined substantially from 18.2 billion rubles ($912 million) in 1991 to 9.5
billion rubles ($10 million) in 1993.  This decline reflects the difficult
experience of Russian industry which has experienced high inflation, loss of
state orders, disruption in traditional supply links and increased import
competition since the dissolution of the Soviet Union.  Traditional medical
industry producers and new private companies are struggling to survive in a
very difficult and uncertain economic market by producing new products, for
the emerging home health care market.  However, the disruptions in local
production have also created additional opportunities for imported products.

Imports

Due to the infancy of the local market for the pertinent products, it is
difficult to estimate shares of locally produced versus imported products.
However, an overview of several medical exhibitions held in Russia in 1993
sheds some light on the Russian market.

According to statistics from the latest medical exhibitions held last year in
St. Petersburg, less than 10% of the participants exhibited equipment that
could be used in home health care or corresponds to the home health care
equipment description given in the Summary.

Most of the exhibitors (40%) were Russian limited companies.  The majority of
these companies represented items produced outside Russia.  Twenty-six
exhibitors were German companies (accounting for 26% of the total
exhibitors), including Dina Handels GMbH, Dornier, Medipart, Dragerwerk and
Omnimed Hammacher Ltd. and others.  Other firms represented were Austrian
(7%), American (6%), and Swedish and Japanese.  Products presented at the
exhibitions included portable diagnostic equipment, individual units and
analyzers for spirometry and lung function measurements, electrocardiographs,
inhalation and aerosol units, rehabilitation units, analytical units,
oximeters and pulsoximeters.

There has been a sharp increase in U.S. exports of medical equipment in
general to Russia in the past three years and experts expect this trend to be
true for imports of home health care equipment as well, although it is
difficult to quantify the volume of exports in such a new market segment.

Competitive Factors

There are already a wide variety and an increasing number of foreign
companies offering their equipment to Russian endusers. Potential Russian
importers are paying close attention to the  following competitive factors:

- price-quality relationship (individuals, as well as companies and clinics,
are searching for quality products at the lowest possible price);

- international reputation of the company (Russian companies are sensitive to
the reputation of foreign firms and the reliability of a foreign partner is a
critical factor for Russian businessmen);

- advertising support for the product's technical advantages and after-sale
service (these are additional indications of company's reliability for a
Russian partner and consumer).


F.  MARKET ACCESS

Currently no customs duties or value added tax on imported medical equipment
and supplies exist.  There are no specific technical standards for medical
equipment, but all products must have a safety certificate from the product's
country of origin.  All products also must have a Registration Certificate
from the Russian Ministry of Health.  Products not already in use (and
therefore, not registered) in Russia must be tested locally by the Russian
Ministry of Health.

All applications for registration should be sent together with the product's
safety certification, to:

