There is no clearly established distribution system or pattern for this
sector at this time.  Some foreign companies that already entered the market
sell their products directly and appointed Russian agents and representatives
to develop their own distribution system.  A few foreign companies have
formed joint ventures with Russian enterprises to produce and sell equipment
for the local market and potentially exports.

We recommend that U.S. exporters first identify the appropriate end-user for
their product, and then determine how the end-users obtain the product on the
local market, i.e., whether through a pharmacy or other distribution chain.
Thereafter, U.S. exporters should seek direct sales or consignment
arrangements with these intermediates (see Key Contact list).  Or
alternatively, they should seek local Russian agents/distributors for their
products.

Following are some recommended approaches for entering the Russian home
health care market:

For immediate sales, it is advisable to rely on local market research to
identify the most popular items.  Advertising plays an important role in
gaining strong product support in the local market.  Some successful
companies have used a variety of advertising, such as TV, public newspapers
and professional publications (magazines and newspapers), to support local
sales.

To enter the market or introduce a new product, professional publications are
definitely helpful since technical descriptions and professional
recommendations are very convincing factors for Russian consumers.

An increasing number of local and foreign producers offer medical equipment
on the Russian market.  Based on their experience, the following appear to be
the most important factors for a successful entrance into the market:

- Using market research and participation in local exhibitions and trade
shows;

- Locating a reliable local partner, since personal business relationships
are important in Russia.  However, we recommend exercising caution in
establishing new partnerships and suggest that exporters always obtain and
verify recommendations or use the World Trader Data Report (WTDR) service
available from U.S.  Department of Commerce District Offices;

- Advertising in professional publications, as well as mass-media advertising
campaigns.

Financing

As there is no reliable credit information on most Russian companies,
suppliers must exercise caution in selling to Russian clients.  Pre-payment
was and still is the best payment protection for the American exporter.
However, the largest importers in Russia currently are seeking protection
against unreliable suppliers.  Consequently, there is a reluctance to pay
100% before delivery.  Therefore, the most common terms of payment are
letter of credit, with a 25% or 50% deposit and payment upon delivery.  In
each case, it is a point of discussion between the parties and the payment
terms will depend on the level of confidence and trust established.

